Description
\f1\b0 : This assignment offers you a deep dive into the world of Clojure. Although any previous experience with the language isn't required, it presents a valuable chance to explore and apply the key concepts of Clojure taught in class. In addition to reinforcing your knowledge of familiar constructs, you'll encounter new ideas and features that will enrich your hands-on experience and enhance your overall programming skills. You'll engage with Clojure's versatile data structures, such as maps, vectors, sets, keywords, and the EDN (Extensible Data Notation) format. By the end of this task, you'll have developed a stronger command of Clojure and its capabilities. \
\
NOTE: Please note that the assignment document may seem lengthy, but the description of the assignment itself is concise and clear. The document primarily consists of valuable hints and advice designed to streamline development of your Clojure program. \
\
Welcome to the Functional Library Information System assignment. Libraries contain large collections of books that must be organized, searched, and analyzed efficiently. In this assignment, you will develop a command-line application that allows users to interact with a collection of books using functional programming principles. The system will allow users to: View books stored in a library collection, Search for books by title or author, Filter books by genre or publication year, Add new books to the collection, Generate useful library statistics and Save changes back to an EDN file. All program logic should be expressed using immutable data structures, pure functions whenever possible, and idiomatic Clojure constructs. You will apply functional operations over collections and will work with immutable updates to persistent data structures. Unlike traditional text-based data files, the library collection will be stored using EDN (Extensible Data Notation), Clojure's native data format. This allows book information to be represented directly as Clojure data structures, simplifying data manipulation and emphasizing the language's strengths. \
\
Data File Format: The application will load book information from an EDN file. \
\
Example: \
[\{:id "B001" \
:title "The Hobbit" \
:author "J.R.R. Tolkien" \
:genre "Fantasy" \
:year 1937\} \
\
\{:id "B002" \
:title "Dune" \
:author "Frank Herbert" \
:genre "Science Fiction" \
:year 1965\} \
\
\{:id "B003" \
:title "Foundation" \
:author "Isaac Asimov" \
:genre "Science Fiction" \
:year 1951\}] \
\
Each book contains the following fields: 
\f0\b id
\f1\b0  ( a unique book identifier), 
\f0\b title
\f1\b0  (the book title), 
\f0\b author
\f1\b0  (Author name), 
\f0\b genre
\f1\b0  (Book genre) and 
\f0\b year
\f1\b0  (Publication year). \
\
Implementation Specifications: Your application must begin by displaying a welcome message and a main menu. It should offer six core options, assuming perfect user input (correct data types and expected formats).\
Here are the menu to implement: \
\
