\f0\b \cf0 \ul \ulc0 1. View Library Collection \

\f1\b0 \ulnone This option displays all books currently stored in the library.\
Requirements:  Display the total number of books. \
Display all books sorted by publication year. \
Display all book information. \
\

\f0\b \ul 2. Search Library \

\f1\b0 \ulnone This option allows users to search for books. \
Sub-menu: \
1. Search by Title The user enters a title fragment.  \
Display all matching books whose titles contain the entered text.\
The search must be case-insensitive. \
2. Search by Author. The user enters an author name or partial author name.  \
Display all matching books. The search must be case-insensitive. \
\

\f0\b \ul 3. Filter Books \

\f1\b0 \ulnone This option enables users to filter the collection. \
Sub-menu: \
1. Filter by Genre. The user enters a genre.  \
Display all books whose genre exactly matches the supplied genre. The comparison should be case-sensitive. \
2. Filter by Publication Year Range. \
The user enters: Minimum year, Maximum year \
\

\f0\b \ul 4. Add a New Book
\f1\b0 \ulnone  \
This option allows users to add a new book to the collection. \
Prompt the user for: Book ID, Title, Author, Genre, Publication Year.\
Create a new book map and add it to the collection.\
\
Example: \{:id "B010" :title "The Martian" :author "Andy Weir" :genre "Science Fiction" :year 2011\} \
After successfully adding the book, display a confirmation message.\
\

\f0\b \ul 5. Library Statistics
\f1\b0 \ulnone  \
Generate the following statistics: Total Number of Books: Display the total number of books currently in the collection. Oldest Book: Display the complete information of the book with the earliest publication year. Newest Book: Display the complete information of the book with the latest publication year. Number of Unique Genres: Using a set, determine number of distinct genres represented in the collection.  Books per Genre: Display the number of books belonging to each genre. \
For example, Fantasy: 12 Science Fiction: 9 History: 5 \
\

\f0\b \ul 6. Save and Exit \

\f1\b0 \ulnone When selected: Save the current collection back to the EDN file. Display a confirmation message. Exit the application.\
\
Required Clojure Features: Your solution must demonstrate the use of:  Maps, Vectors, Keywords, Sets, Higher-order functions (map, filter, reduce), Immutable updates, File I/O, EDN reading and writing, User-defined functions and Menu-driven program design\
\

\f0\b Assumptions: \

\f1\b0 You may assume: \
\'95 The user always enters valid menu options. \
\'95 The EDN file is correctly formatted. \'95 Publication years are valid integers. \
\'95 Book IDs are unique. \
\'95 No error handling is required for invalid input. \
\

\f0\b MANDATORY DATA STRUCTURES AND FUNCTIONAL PROGRAMMING USAGE: 
\f1\b0 \
1. Maps: Each book must be represented as a map containing the following keys: :id :title :author :genre :year.\
All book information must be stored and manipulated using maps. \
2. Vectors: The entire library collection must be stored in a vector of book maps.\
Vector operations should be used when traversing, filtering, sorting, and updating the collection. \
3. Sets: Sets must be used to determine the number of distinct genres present in the library collection.\
Appropriate set operations should be used whenever unique values are required. \
4. EDN: The library collection must be loaded from an EDN file at program startup. \
The updated collection must be written back to an EDN file when the user selects Save and Exit. \
Students are expected to use the clojure.edn library for reading and writing data. \
5. Searching and Filtering: The Search Library and Filter Books features must be implemented using higher-order functions.The filter function should be used to identify books that satisfy user-specified criteria. \
6. Sorting: Books displayed through the View Library Collection option must be sorted by publication year.\
The sort-by function should be used to perform sorting operations. \
7. Statistics and Data Analysis: Library statistics must be computed using functional operations over collections.\
Functions such as group-by, frequencies, map, and reduce should be used where appropriate to generate statistical summaries. \
8. Immutable Updates: Adding a new book must not modify an existing collection directly. \
A new collection containing the additional book should be created using immutable collection operations such as conj. \
9. Functional Programming Requirements: Core application logic must be implemented using pure functions where possible. Explicit state mutation using atom, ref, agent, mutable Java collections, or similar mechanisms is not permitted. \
Input/output operations should be confined to dedicated functions responsible for user interaction and file processing. Students are expected to make meaningful use of higher-order functions such as: map, filter, reduce, group-by, sort-by and frequencies. Failure to demonstrate meaningful use of the required data structures and functional programming techniques may result in deductions, even if the program produces correct output.\
\
